                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, April 25 (PTI): A disruption in an undersea cable system, which links South East Asia and Europe, is likely to affect broadband services in India in the next four days.           
	The South East Asia-Middle East-West Europe 4 project links the two regions via the Indian sub continent and West Asia. The project is run by a consortium of 16 international telecom companies, including Bharti Airtel and Tata Communications.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The central paramilitary forces are seeking a post-retirement resettlement plan for sniffer dogs to prevent them from falling into the hands of terrorists and criminals. The sniffer dogs, who detect explosives and drugs, have a working life of about 10 years in a 14-year lifespan. Once retired, they are vulnerable to manipulation by militants and terrorists.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The government has decided to install radiation monitor portals at all ports and entry points in the country amid reports that the recent radiation leak in west Delhi may have happened because of scrap brought in from outside.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The government has launched a project in 22 states for biometric identification of suspected criminals. The governments will take the fingerprints of hard-core criminals and store them in a database, which can be accessed by investigative and security agencies from anywhere in the country.                  
	 Erode (PTI): Nine Dalit children and six others were rescued from bondage by revenue officials from a brick kiln at Kalingarayanpalayam near Erode. Fifteen people from Kattuserry village were being forced to work as bonded labourers in the brick kiln.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): An automatic train washing plant, which the Delhi Metro claims to be the highest in Asia, is coming up in the capital. Its being built on a ramp at a height of 6.7 metres from the ground level and can clean two Metro trains in just five minutes with the help of vertical brushes.                                                                                                                                              
